The temperament of dwarfed dogs are typically aggressive and anxious , which make for undesirable pets, resulting in breeders usually being forced to euthanize a puppy born with dwarfism.

Tiger's owner John Coleman told the Daily Mail Australia that to euthanize was never an option.

Eight years ago Mr Coleman and his partner Nick had purchased a full grown German Shepherd from breeders Darien and Ken Northcote.

It wasn't until five years later when Mr Coleman received a call from the Northcotes, telling him of their recent breed of genetically mutated German Shepherds and asking him if he would be willing to adopt a mutated dog with dwarfism.

'We did a pretty good job with our full grown dog, Lydia, so they [Northcotes] thought we would be the best people to take on Tiger,' he said.

